messages.content:
Below is a **step‑by‑step guide** that shows how to turn the sketch you posted into a **Matter “Shade” (Window‑Covering) controller that binds to a contact‑sensor’s BooleanState attribute**.  
The focus is on the **root‑node binding cluster**, **subscribing to the remote attribute**, **robust event handling**, and **rejecting unwanted bindings**.

---

## 1. High‑level Architecture

```
+---------------------------+                     +---------------------------+
|   ESP32‑Matter (Server)   |   <--- Binding ---> |   Remote Contact Sensor    |
|   (WindowCovering EP)     |   (Cluster: Binding)   (Server)                   |
|   - Binding cluster (EP0) |                     |   - BooleanState cluster  |
|   - WindowCovering EP     |                     +---------------------------+
|   - Subscription client   |
+---------------------------+
```

* **Root endpoint (EP 0)** holds the **Binding cluster** (ID 0x000F).  
* The **Window‑Covering endpoint** (e.g. EP 1) is the “shade”.  
* When the user creates a binding (via a controller UI) that points to a *Contact‑Sensor* node, the **Binding table entry** will look like:

| FabricIdx | NodeId (remote) | EndpointId | ClusterId (BooleanState) |  AttributeId (StateValue) |
|-----------|----------------|------------|--------------------------|---------------------------|

* After the entry appears we **subscribe** to that remote attribute.  
* Every time the contact sensor toggles, we get a **ReadClient callback** that tells us the new boolean value.  
* The callback drives the local motor (or, in our case, just toggles the “open/close” GPIOs).

---

## 2. Adding the Binding Cluster to the Root Node

The Binding cluster is already created in your code (the `#ifdef CONFIG_SUBSCRIBE_AFTER_BINDING` block).  
If you want it only when the feature is enabled, keep the `#ifdef` guard; otherwise just move the call out of the guard so the cluster is always present.

```cpp
// --------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 1️⃣ Create the Binding cluster on the *root* endpoint (EP 0)
// --------------------------------------------------------------------------
cluster::binding::config_t bind_cfg;                     // empty config – no mandatory attributes
cluster::binding::create(root_node_ep, &bind_cfg, CLUSTER_FLAG_SERVER);
```

> **Why root endpoint?**  
> The Matter spec mandates that the *Binding* cluster live on the *root* (endpoint 0).  
> The server side will emit `kBindingsChangedViaCluster` whenever the table is edited, which we can catch in `app_event_cb`.

---

## 3. Hooking the “Binding Changed” Event

Matter already posts `kBindingsChangedViaCluster`. In `app_event_cb` you already log it.  
Replace the simple log with a **handler that initiates a subscription** for each newly added entry.

```cpp
static void handle_binding_changed(void)
{
    // 1️⃣  Get the current binding table
    const chip::BindingTable &table = chip::BindingTable::GetInstance();
    size_t entry_count = table.Size();

    ESP_LOGI(TAG, "Binding table now has %zu entries", entry_count);

    // 2️⃣  Walk the table and subscribe to any BooleanState entry that we have not yet subscribed to
    for (size_t i = 0; i < entry_count; ++i) {
        const chip::BindingTable::Entry &e = table[i];
        // Only care about remote nodes (node_id != 0) and the BooleanState cluster
        if (e.nodeId == 0) continue; // local binding – ignore for our use‑case
        if (e.clusterId != chip::app::Clusters::BooleanState::Id) continue;

        // ------------------------------------------------------------------
        // Build a *subscription* request for attribute StateValue (0x0000)
        // ------------------------------------------------------------------
        chip::app::AttributePathParams attr_path;
        attr_path.mEndpointId   = static_cast<chip::EndpointId>(e.endpointId);
        attr_path.mClusterId    = static_cast<chip::ClusterId>(e.clusterId);
        attr_path.mFieldId      = static_cast<chip::AttributeId>(chip::app::Clusters::BooleanState::Attributes::StateValue::Id);
        attr_path.mFlags        = chip::app::AttributePathParams::Flags::kFieldIdValid;

        // Store a copy of the binding entry so we can identify it later
        // (e.g. for unsubscription when the entry disappears)
        // We'll keep a tiny struct in a static vector – see section 5.
        subscribe_to_remote(attr_path, e);
    }
}
```

Add a call to `handle_binding_changed()` inside the `kBindingsChangedViaCluster` case:

```cpp
case chip::DeviceLayer::DeviceEventType::kBindingsChangedViaCluster: {
    ESP_LOGI(TAG, "Bindings changed via cluster");
    handle_binding_changed();        // <‑‑ NEW
    break;
}
```

---

## 4. Setting Up the *Client* Side – Request Callback + Subscription

### 4.1 Register a global request‑callback

The `esp_matter::client::set_request_callback()` function is the *single entry point* that tells us when a **CASE session** has been opened (or when a group request is ready).  
We use it to launch the actual `ReadClient` once the session is established.

```cpp
static void request_send_cb(peer_device_t *peer, request_handle_t *req, void *priv)
{
    // This callback is invoked for *every* request we asked the SDK to send.
    // For subscriptions we only need the peer device – the request_handle
    // already contains the attribute_path we built earlier.
    ESP_LOGI(TAG, "CASE session ready – peer 0x%016llx", peer->GetDeviceId());

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 2️⃣  Build a ReadClient (subscription) for the attribute we want
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    using namespace esp_matter::client::interaction;
    esp_err_t err = subscribe::send_request(
        peer,
        /*attr_path*/ nullptr, /*attr_path_size*/ 0,
        /*event_path*/ nullptr, /*event_path_size*/ 0,
        /*min_interval*/ 0,  /*max_interval*/ 60,
        /*keep_subscription*/ true,
        /*auto_resubscribe*/ true,
        /*callback*/ subscription_cb);   // see 4.2

    if (err != ESP_OK) {
        ESP_LOGE(TAG, "Failed to start subscription: %s", esp_err_to_name(err));
    }
}
```

Register it **once** after `node::create()` (or right before `esp_matter::start()`):

```cpp
esp_matter::client::set_request_callback(request_send_cb, nullptr, nullptr);
```

> **Why `nullptr` for group callback?**  
> We are not using group bindings for the shade; we only need unicast.

### 4.2 The `ReadClient::Callback` implementation

We need a **stateful** callback that can decode the TLV payload and act on the value.

```cpp
class ShadeSubscriptionCallback : public chip::app::ReadClient::Callback {
public:
    // ctx can be a pointer to your shade‑controller object (or nullptr)
    explicit ShadeSubscriptionCallback(void *ctx = nullptr) : mCtx(ctx) {}

    // Called when the subscription *initial* report arrives (or any subsequent report)
    void OnReportBegin() override { /* no‑op */ }

    // Called for each attribute that the server reports
    void OnAttributeData(const chip::app::ConcreteDataAttributePath &path,
                         chip::TLV::TLVReader &data,
                         const chip::app::StatusIB *status) override
    {
        // Verify we are looking at the BooleanState::StateValue attribute
        if (path.mClusterId != chip::app::Clusters::BooleanState::Id ||
            path.mAttributeId != chip::app::Clusters::BooleanState::Attributes::StateValue::Id) {
            ESP_LOGW(TAG, "Unexpected attribute: cluster 0x%04x attr 0x%04x",
                     path.mClusterId, path.mAttributeId);
            return;
        }

        bool state = false;
        chip::TLV::TLVType outer;
        CHIP_ERROR err = data.GetTag(&outer);
        if (err == CHIP_NO_ERROR) {
            // The attribute is a simple boolean – decode directly
            err = data.Get(state);
        }

        if (err != CHIP_NO_ERROR) {
            ESP_LOGE(TAG, "Failed to decode BooleanState::StateValue: %s", chip::ErrorStr(err));
            return;
        }

        ESP_LOGI(TAG, "Contact sensor reported state=%s", state ? "CLOSED" : "OPEN");
        // ------------------------------------------------------------------
        // 3️⃣  Drive the local shade based on the remote contact sensor
        // ------------------------------------------------------------------
        handle_remote_contact(state);
    }

    void OnError(CHIP_ERROR error) override
    {
        ESP_LOGE(TAG, "Subscription error: %s", chip::ErrorStr(error));
    }

    void OnDone(chip::app::ReadClient *client) override
    {
        ESP_LOGI(TAG, "Subscription finished (client %p)", client);
        // The SDK will automatically restart if auto_resubscribe was true.
    }

private:
    void *mCtx;
};

static ShadeSubscriptionCallback subscription_cb;   // static – lives for the lifetime of the app
```

**Important notes**

* **`auto_resubscribe = true`** ensures that the SDK will re‑establish the subscription if the CASE session drops (e.g. after a reboot of the remote sensor).  
* **`keep_subscription = true`** tells the SDK to keep the subscription alive after the first report.  

---

## 5. Keeping Track of *Which* Remote We Are Subscribed To

When a binding entry is removed we should **cancel the subscription** to avoid stray callbacks.  
A lightweight way is to store a small map of **binding‑key → ReadClient** (or just a flag, because we only have one subscription per remote).

```cpp
struct RemoteBindingKey {
    uint64_t node_id;   // remote node id
    uint16_t endpoint;  // remote endpoint
    bool operator==(const RemoteBindingKey &other) const {
        return node_id == other.node_id && endpoint == other.endpoint;
    }
};

struct RemoteBindingKeyHash {
    size_t operator()(const RemoteBindingKey &k) const noexcept {
        return std::hash<uint64_t>{}(k.node_id) ^ (std::hash<uint16_t>{}(k.endpoint) << 1);
    }
};

static std::unordered_map<RemoteBindingKey, chip::app::ReadClient *, RemoteBindingKeyHash> gActiveSubs;
```

Update `subscribe_to_remote()` (the helper we called from `handle_binding_changed()`):

```cpp
static void subscribe_to_remote(const chip::app::AttributePathParams &attr_path,
                                const chip::BindingTable::Entry &bind_entry)
{
    // Build a key that uniquely identifies the remote node/endpoint
    RemoteBindingKey key{ bind_entry.nodeId, bind_entry.endpointId };

    // If we already have a subscription for this key, skip
    if (gActiveSubs.find(key) != gActiveSubs.end()) {
        ESP_LOGD(TAG, "Already subscribed to node 0x%llx ep %u", key.node_id, key.endpoint);
        return;
    }

    // Ask the SDK to open a CASE session and then call request_send_cb
    request_handle_t req{};
    req.type = client::request_type_t::SUBSCRIBE_ATTR;
    req.attribute_path = attr_path;   // copy
    req.request_data = nullptr;       // not used for subscribe

    // Store the key in the request handle’s priv_data so request_send_cb can
    // retrieve it later (optional – we can also just look it up again later)
    RemoteBindingKey *priv = new RemoteBindingKey(key);
    req.request_data = priv;          // will be freed in the callback after use

    // Kick off the connection – the request_send_cb will be invoked when the
    // session is ready.
    esp_err_t err = esp_matter::client::connect(
        esp_matter::case_session_mgr_t::GetInstance(),
        /*fabric_index*/ 0,                 // 0 = current fabric
        bind_entry.nodeId,
        &req);

    if (err != ESP_OK) {
        ESP_LOGE(TAG, "Failed to start CASE session: %s", esp_err_to_name(err));
        delete priv;
    } else {
        // Remember that we have an outstanding request; the real subscription
        // will be created inside request_send_cb.
        gActiveSubs.emplace(key, nullptr); // placeholder – will be filled later
    }
}
```

In `request_send_cb` after we successfully create the `ReadClient`, **store the pointer**:

```cpp
static void request_send_cb(peer_device_t *peer, request_handle_t *req, void *priv_data)
{
    // ... same as before ...

    // Build the subscription (same as before)
    esp_err_t err = esp_matter::client::interaction::subscribe::send_request(
        peer,
        /*attr_path*/ nullptr, 0,
        /*event_path*/ nullptr, 0,
        /*min_interval*/ 0, /*max_interval*/ 60,
        /*keep_subscription*/ true,
        /*auto_resubscribe*/ true,
        subscription_cb);

    if (err == ESP_OK && req->request_data) {
        // The request_data points to our RemoteBindingKey we allocated earlier
        RemoteBindingKey *key = static_cast<RemoteBindingKey *>(req->request_data);
        // Update the map with the real ReadClient (the SDK stores it inside the callback object)
        // The SDK does not give us the ReadClient pointer directly, but we can keep the
        // subscription_cb object itself – it is static – so we just set the map entry to a sentinel.
        // For a production code you might want a per‑binding callback object.
        gActiveSubs[*key] = nullptr; // we don't need the pointer now
        delete key; // clean up
    }
}
```

When a binding entry disappears we need to **cancel** the subscription. The SDK does not expose a direct “unsubscribe” API, but you can **close the ReadClient** (by calling `ReadClient::Shutdown()`). Since we kept a static callback, we’ll just **clear the map** – the SDK will automatically tear down the session when the client object goes out of scope. If you need explicit teardown, allocate a per‑binding `ReadClient` object and keep it in the map; then call `client->Shutdown()` when the entry is removed.

For brevity the example keeps a *single* static callback; that works fine as long as you have **at most one remote contact sensor** bound to the shade. If you need multiple, allocate a distinct `ReadClient` per entry (see `client::interaction::read::send_request` overload that takes a `ReadClient::Callback&` you allocate on the heap).

---

## 6. Driving the Shade – The `handle_remote_contact()` Function

```cpp
static void handle_remote_contact(bool closed)
{
    // In a classic shade you would drive a motor until it reaches a limit.
    // Here we just turn GPIOs on/off (open/close) based on the contact state.
    if (closed) {
        // Contact says "closed" → shade should be *down*
        gpio_set_level(GPIO_OUTPUT_COVER_CLOSE, 1);
        gpio_set_level(GPIO_OUTPUT_COVER_OPEN,  0);
        ESP_LOGI(TAG, "Shade: CLOSE (contact CLOSED)");
    } else {
        // Contact says "open" → shade should be *up*
        gpio_set_level(GPIO_OUTPUT_COVER_OPEN,  1);
        gpio_set_level(GPIO_OUTPUT_COVER_CLOSE, 0);
        ESP_LOGI(TAG, "Shade: OPEN (contact OPEN)");
    }
}
```

You can replace the simple GPIO toggling with your **motor‑control state machine** (the code you already have for `window_covering` commands). The important part is that the **boolean value** is now a reliable trigger coming from the bound sensor.

---

## 7. Rejecting Unwanted Bindings (Constraints)

Matter’s **Binding cluster** implements the `Bind` command (ID 0x00).  
You can install a **custom command callback** for that command and decide, at runtime, whether the request is accepted.

### 7.1 Create the command object and set a user callback

```cpp
// After you created the binding cluster on EP0:
cluster_t *binding_cluster = cluster::binding::create(root_node_ep, &bind_cfg, CLUSTER_FLAG_SERVER);
ABORT_APP_ON_FAILURE(binding_cluster != nullptr, ESP_LOGE(TAG, "Failed to create binding cluster"));

// Get the Bind command object (generated in zap)
command_t *bind_cmd = cluster::binding::command::create_bind(binding_cluster);
ABORT_APP_ON_FAILURE(bind_cmd != nullptr, ESP_LOGE(TAG, "Failed to get Bind command"));

// Install our validator
command::set_user_callback(bind_cmd, bind_command_validator);
```

### 7.2 The validator implementation

```cpp
static esp_err_t bind_command_validator(const ConcreteCommandPath &cmd_path,
                                        TLVReader &tlv_data,
                                        void *opaque_ptr)
{
    // The payload of the Bind command is a Binding struct:
    //   nodeId, groupId, endpointId, clusterId, fabricIndex
    // We only care about remote (nodeId != 0) bindings that target
    // BooleanState::StateValue.
    chip::Binding::Target target;
    CHIP_ERROR err = chip::Binding::ReadFromTLV(tlv_data, target);
    if (err != CHIP_NO_ERROR) {
        ESP_LOGE(TAG, "Failed to decode Bind command: %s", chip::ErrorStr(err));
        return ESP_ERR_INVALID_ARG;
    }

    // ---- Constraint #1: Must be a *contact sensor* (i.e. BooleanState) ----
    if (target.clusterId != chip::app::Clusters::BooleanState::Id ||
        target.attributeId != chip::app::Clusters::BooleanState::Attributes::StateValue::Id) {
        ESP_LOGW(TAG, "Rejecting Bind: only BooleanState::StateValue allowed");
        // Return a Matter status – the SDK will translate it to a ZCL error.
        // Use StatusIB with a generic “InvalidCommand” or “UnsupportedCluster”.
        // For simplicity we return ESP_ERR_NOT_SUPPORTED which ends up as
        // 0x85 (UnsupportedCluster) to the client.
        return ESP_ERR_NOT_SUPPORTED;
    }

    // ---- Constraint #2: Optional – verify that the remote node is a Contact‑Sensor device type ----
    // The nodeId alone is not enough to know the device type.  You could request the
    // Descriptor::DeviceTypeList attribute from the remote node and verify that it contains
    // ESP_MATTER_CONTACT_SENSOR_DEVICE_TYPE_ID (0x0015).  That requires an extra read,
    // which is optional.  Here we just allow any node that binds to the attribute.
    // If you want the extra verification, you can do an async read here and return
    // ESP_ERR_BUSY (the SDK will reply with “Failure”); when the read completes you
    // can send a *Write* to the Binding cluster with the *status* you want.

    ESP_LOGI(TAG, "Binding accepted – node 0x%llx ep %u", target.nodeId, target.endpointId);
    return ESP_OK;   // Accept the binding
}
```

**What happens when you return an error?**  
The SDK translates the `esp_err_t` into a Matter `StatusIB` response.  
Typical values:

| `esp_err_t`                | Matter status (hex) | Meaning                               |
|----------------------------|---------------------|---------------------------------------|
| `ESP_OK`                   | 0x00                | Success                               |
| `ESP_ERR_NOT_SUPPORTED`    | 0x85                | Unsupported cluster/attribute          |
| `ESP_ERR_INVALID_ARG`      | 0x87                | Invalid command/field                  |
| `ESP_ERR_NO_MEM`           | 0x89                | Insufficient resources                |
| `ESP_ERR_NOT_FOUND`        | 0x86                | Not found (e.g. node does not exist)  |

Thus you have full control over **which bindings are allowed**.

### 7.3 Optional: Enforce a *single* contact sensor per shade

If you only want **one** sensor bound, keep a static flag:

```cpp
static bool gContactSensorBound = false;

static esp_err_t bind_command_validator(const ConcreteCommandPath &cmd_path,
                                        TLVReader &tlv_data,
                                        void *opaque_ptr)
{
    // Decode as before …
    if (gContactSensorBound) {
        ESP_LOGW(TAG, "Rejecting extra Bind – already have one sensor");
        return ESP_ERR_INVALID_STATE;   // 0x88 (InvalidState)
    }
    // Accept …
    gContactSensorBound = true;
    return ESP_OK;
}
```

When the binding entry is removed (you’ll get a `kBindingsChangedViaCluster` event), scan the table again and clear the flag if the entry disappeared.

