## 10. Edge‑Case Handling & Production Tips

| Situation | Recommended handling |
|-----------|----------------------|
| **CASE session drops** (remote reboots) | `auto_resubscribe = true` already handles it. The SDK will re‑open the session and re‑issue the subscription. |
| **Multiple contact sensors bound** | Extend `gActiveSubs` to store a **ReadClient** per key. In `OnAttributeData` you can decide which sensor has priority (e.g., last‑change wins). |
| **Binding table overflow** (max 16 entries on ESP32) | Guard in `bind_command_validator` – if `chip::BindingTable::GetInstance().Size() >= 16` return `ESP_ERR_NO_MEM`. |
| **Security** – reject bindings from unknown fabrics | In the validator you can check `cmd_path.mFabricIndex` (available via `cmd_path.mFabricIndex`) against `chip::FabricTable::GetInstance().GetCurrentFabricIndex()`. |
| **Memory leaks** – request_handle.request_data** | In the examples we allocate a `RemoteBindingKey` only when we need it and free it inside `request_send_cb`. If you store a heap‑allocated `ReadClient`, make sure you `Shutdown()` and delete it when the binding disappears. |
| **Power‑loss recovery** – re‑establish subscriptions after reboot | On boot, after `esp_matter::start()` you will receive a `kBindingsChangedViaCluster` event for the persisted table (the binding table is stored in NVS). `handle_binding_changed()` will automatically resubscribe. |
| **Debugging TLV** – use `chip::Debug::PrintValue` or `chip::LogError` to dump the raw TLV if you suspect malformed data. |

